				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\cdot $$\end{document}SnF2), which was proved to eliminate the phase separation caused by SnF2 in the perovskite and passivate the perovskite films [38, 39]. An amine complex, CH3NH3I·3CH3NH2 (MAI·3MA), was introduced simultaneously with SnF2 to hinder the major issue caused by the oxidation of Sn2+ to Sn4+. Like the aforementioned TMA additive, the presence of electron-donating additive MAI·3MA would tend to favor the formation of SnI2 complexes and thus slow down the consumption as a product in the global crystallization reaction. The resulted optimized films were more stable with decreased defect density (from 6.50 ×\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
