Recently, inorganic CsSnI3 have received more attention due to its small optical bandgap. Wang et al. studied the coadditive 2-aminopyrazine (APZ) to form SnF2–APZ complex in CsSnI3 precursor, aiming at restrain Sn2+ oxidation and improve device performance. As shown in Fig. 2e, SnF2 have a strong binging affinity with APZ to form complexes. Such coordination was proved by Fourier-transform infrared (FTIR) spectroscopy; the characteristic C=N stretching vibration shifted to a higher wavenumber than that without SnF2. The shift could be attributed to the d→π∗\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
