Wang et al. introduced cobaltocene (CoCp2) as a chemical doping agent that could donate the electron to CsSnI3 to offer the capability of suppressing Sn2+ oxidization and lower the trap density. As shown in Fig. 3e, CoCp2 is a commonly one-electron reducing agent which can easily give up an extra electron from the metal cobalt to form an 18-electron cation with high stability. The XPS measurement confirmed the occurrence of a substantial electron transfer from CoCp2 to CsSnI3 and thus reducing the self-doping effect. In particular, the average lifetime was enhanced from 3.66 to 8.71 ns and the trap density decreased from 1.08 ×\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
